        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## What Is a GLM?\n",
        "\n",
        "A **generalized linear model (GLM)** extends ordinary linear regression in two ways:\n",
        "\n",
        "- the response variable does not need to be normally distributed;\n",
        "- the mean of the response is connected to the predictors through a **link function**.\n",
        "\n",
        "A GLM has three components:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. A response distribution from the exponential family, such as Gaussian, Binomial, or Poisson.\n",
        "2. A linear predictor\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\eta = X\\beta.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "3. A link function relating the mean $\\mu = \\mathbb{E}(Y \\mid X)$ to the linear predictor:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "g(\\mu) = \\eta = X\\beta.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Thus, a GLM keeps the predictor linear in the coefficients, but it allows the response distribution and the mean-response relationship to be more flexible than in ordinary linear regression.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## Main Idea\n",
        "\n",
        "Linear regression models the response directly under a Gaussian error assumption. A GLM models the mean of the response through a link function and can handle binary, count, and other non-Gaussian outcomes.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## Why Do We Need GLMs?\n",
        "\n",
        "Ordinary linear regression is not always appropriate.\n",
        "\n",
        "- For binary outcomes, fitted values from linear regression may fall outside $[0,1]$.\n",
        "- For count data, the response is nonnegative and often right-skewed.\n",
        "- The variance may depend on the mean, which violates the constant-variance assumption of linear regression.\n",
        "\n",
        "GLMs address these issues by choosing a distribution and a link function suited to the data.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## Common Examples\n",
        "\n",
        "### Linear Regression\n",
        "\n",
        "For a Gaussian response with the identity link,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mu = X\\beta.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This is the ordinary linear model.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Logistic Regression\n",
        "\n",
        "For binary data, logistic regression uses\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\log\\left(\\frac{\\mu}{1-\\mu}\\right) = X\\beta,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $\\mu = \\mathbb{P}(Y=1 \\mid X)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Poisson Regression\n",
        "\n",
        "For count data, Poisson regression uses\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\log(\\mu) = X\\beta,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $\\mu = \\mathbb{E}(Y \\mid X)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## Relation to Linear Regression\n",
        "\n",
        "A GLM is not the same as transforming the response and then applying ordinary least squares.\n",
        "\n",
        "For example,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\log(Y) = X\\beta + \\varepsilon\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "is a transformed linear model, whereas\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\log(\\mathbb{E}[Y \\mid X]) = X\\beta\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "is a GLM with a log link.\n",
        "\n",
        "These models may look similar algebraically, but they differ in assumptions, interpretation, and estimation.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## Estimation\n",
        "\n",
        "Unlike ordinary least squares, GLMs are usually estimated by **maximum likelihood**, often using **iteratively reweighted least squares (IRLS)**.\n",
        "\n",
        "The details of the algorithm are usually less important than the modeling idea:\n",
        "\n",
        "- choose a suitable distribution;\n",
        "- choose a suitable link function;\n",
        "- interpret the fitted model on the correct scale.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## Interpretation\n",
        "\n",
        "The coefficients in a GLM are interpreted through the link function.\n",
        "\n",
        "- In logistic regression, coefficients describe changes in log-odds.\n",
        "- In Poisson regression, coefficients describe changes in the log mean count.\n",
        "- In linear regression, coefficients describe direct changes in the mean response.\n",
        "\n",
        "Therefore, interpretation depends on both the response distribution and the link.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## Relation to GAMs and Regularization\n",
        "\n",
        "GLMs still assume that the predictor enters through the linear form $X\\beta$. A **generalized additive model (GAM)** relaxes this by replacing linear terms with smooth functions:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "g(\\mu) = \\beta_0 + f_1(x_1) + \\cdots + f_p(x_p).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Regularization methods such as ridge regression and LASSO can also be combined with GLMs, producing penalized logistic regression, penalized Poisson regression, and related models.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## Python Example\n",
        "\n",
        "The following example fits a logistic regression model in Python using the public `titanic` dataset from `seaborn`. It includes coefficient tables, fitted probabilities, a classification table, and standard residual and influence diagnostics."
      ],
