        "Here the response `survived` is binary, so a binomial GLM with a logit link is appropriate. The terms `C(sex)` and `C(pclass)` tell `statsmodels` to treat those variables as categorical predictors.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "## Similarities and Differences Between LM and GLM\n",
        "\n",
        "A linear model (LM) and a generalized linear model (GLM) are closely related. In fact, the ordinary linear regression model can be viewed as a special case of a GLM.\n",
        "\n",
        "They are similar in several important ways:\n",
        "\n",
        "- both relate a response variable to predictors;\n",
        "- both use a linear predictor of the form $X\\beta$;\n",
        "- both allow categorical variables, interactions, and transformed predictors;\n",
        "- both produce coefficient estimates, fitted values, residuals, and model summaries.\n",
        "\n",
        "However, they differ in the way the response is modeled.\n",
        "\n",
        "In a linear model, we write\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "Y = X\\beta + \\varepsilon,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "with a Gaussian error assumption and constant variance.\n",
        "\n",
        "In a GLM, we model the mean of the response through a link function:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "g(\\mu) = X\\beta, \\qquad \\mu = \\mathbb{E}(Y \\mid X).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Thus, the major differences are:\n",
        "\n",
        "- an LM models the response directly;\n",
        "- a GLM models the mean of the response through a link function;\n",
        "- an LM usually assumes Gaussian errors with constant variance;\n",
        "- a GLM allows other response distributions such as Binomial or Poisson;\n",
        "- an LM is usually estimated by ordinary least squares;\n",
        "- a GLM is usually estimated by maximum likelihood.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## A Useful Way to Think About It\n",
        "\n",
        "An LM is appropriate when the response is quantitative and approximately normal with constant variance. A GLM is appropriate when the response has a different distributional form, such as binary outcomes or counts, but we still want a regression model built from the linear predictor $X\\beta$.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "The two models can also look algebraically similar. For example,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\log(Y) = X\\beta + \\varepsilon\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "is a transformed linear model, whereas\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\log(\\mathbb{E}[Y \\mid X]) = X\\beta\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "is a GLM with a log link. These are not the same model, even though the equations look similar. They differ in interpretation, assumptions, and estimation.\n",
        "\n",
        "So the main relationship is:\n",
        "\n",
        "- an LM is a special case of a GLM;\n",
        "- a GLM keeps the linear predictor but generalizes the response distribution and the mean-response relationship."
